# Website Icon RTL Flip (`Icn` `flp`)

Applies when authoring or editing website UI that renders a directional icon (arrow, chevron pointing a way, play, back, forward, etc.) via `Icn` (`website/src/app/ui/base/components/Utils.tsx`).

## Rule

`Icn` adds the CSS class `no-flip` by **default** (when `flp` is falsy). The global stylesheet (`website/src/resources/emotion/styles/global.ts`) mirrors icons in RTL only when `no-flip` is **absent**:

```css
html[dir=rtl] { .me-icon:not(.no-flip) { transform: scaleX(-1) !important; } }
```

`react-icons` get the `me-icon` class via `MyApp`'s `IconContext.Provider` (`className: "me-icon"`).

Therefore:
- A **directional** icon that must point the reading-forward direction (e.g. `FiArrowRight`, `FiChevronRight` used as "next/forward/explore") MUST pass `flp` so `no-flip` is dropped and the icon mirrors in Arabic. In LTR it keeps its native direction; in RTL it flips.
- A **non-directional** icon (`FiMapPin`, `FiBriefcase`, `FiBell`, `FiUser`, …) MUST **not** pass `flp` — the default `no-flip` keeps it unmirrored (a pin or bell flipping in RTL is wrong).

## Why

Without `flp`, a forward-arrow stays right-pointing in Arabic, contradicting the RTL reading direction — a silent, hard-to-spot visual bug. The opt-in (`flp`) keeps non-directional icons correct by default and makes mirroring explicit for directional ones.

## Canonical case

`CustomerHeroSlider` slide CTA chip arrow (`website/src/app/ui/components/customer/home/CustomerHeroSlider.tsx`):

```tsx
<Icn As={FiArrowRight} size={"0.8rem"} color={"@white"} flp/>
```

The `flp` makes `FiArrowRight` point left in Arabic (RTL) and right in English (LTR).

## Authority

- `website/src/app/ui/base/components/Utils.tsx` (`Icn` → `classNames({"no-flip": !flp}, ...)`)
- `website/src/resources/emotion/styles/global.ts` (`html[dir=rtl] .me-icon:not(.no-flip)`)
- `website/src/app/ui/base/core/MyApp.tsx` (`IconContext.Provider` `className: "me-icon"`)
- `docs/platforms/website/flow-customer-shell.md` (hero CTA arrow)
